ce:section.ce:para:
Yang et al. developed a MIP/CDs-based nanosensor towards an insecticide fipronil in environmental samples including tap water and food samples including milk and egg samples [69]. For this aim, the researchers firstly synthesized green CDs from citric acid applying hydrothermal method. Then, molecularly imprinted silica was prepared utilizing sol-gel technique using 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane (APTES) and tetraethoxysilane (TEOS) were chosen as the functional monomer and cross-linker, respectively. The developed sensor displayed high recognition efficiency and selectivity for the target insecticide fipronil in real environmental and food samples (

                        Fig. 1
                        ). It also exhibited satisfactory linearity in terms of sensing response which vary between 0.70 pM and 47 µM. In addition, an excellent limit of detection value (19 pM) was achieved. As conclusion, the superior features of the developed approach in this work such as excellent sensitivity, selectivity, low cost and wide concentration range make it an appropriate and powerful candidate for the effective sensing of various pesticides such as fipronil in real samples. Furthermore, it is worthy to note that the develop approach is unavailable in the case of the strongly basic or acidic environments because of some stability issues of the fabricated MIP/CDs-based nanosensor.
